      commentary: `The Gāyatrī — the most revered of all Vedic meters — is more than a poetic form. It is the meter of the Gāyatrī mantra, the solar invocation that Vedic tradition considers the mother of all mantras. Its twenty-four syllables carry within them the structural pattern through which the divine illuminates the mind. The divine in the domain of sacred sound is most present in what most directly invokes illumination.\n\nMārgaśīrṣa — the month of early winter in the Indian calendar, approximately November-December, considered auspicious and clear, when the crops are in and the air is fresh. Among all the months, the divine is most present in the one that carries clarity, abundance, and the crisp quality of air that has cooled from summer's heat.\n\nKusumākaraḥ — the spring, the season of flowering. Among all the seasons, the divine is most concentrated in spring: the explosion of life returning after winter, every tree flowering simultaneously, the earth renewing itself with unreserved generosity. The vibhūti of spring is the divine's self-expression as the inexhaustible generativity of life — the way existence loves to burst into form.`
