      commentary: `Gambling among the deceitful — this is one of the most provocative vibhūtis. The divine is not located in gambling as a moral example; gambling is named as the most complete expression of the principle of uncertain outcome, of the domain where chance, skill, psychology, and fate all converge. In the very element of risk itself — the moment of the die's fall when the outcome is still open — there is the divine's expression of the radical openness of existence.\n\nTejah — splendor, radiance, the inner luminosity that some human beings carry. Among all the forms of brilliance — physical beauty, intellectual power, artistic excellence, spiritual radiance — the divine is the quality of splendor itself. When you encounter someone or something that seems to shine with an inner light, you are encountering this vibhūti.\n\nSattvam sattvavatām — the goodness of the good. Among all those who embody the quality of sattva — purity, clarity, luminous virtue — the divine is most present in the goodness itself. Not the person who is good, but the quality of goodness expressed through them. When you witness genuine virtue, genuine care, genuine integrity — you are in the presence of this vibhūti.`
