      commentary: `The vibhūti list concludes with perhaps the most universal statement: bījaṁ tad aham — I am the seed of all beings. The seed contains the entire future plant in potential; it is the condensed possibility of all future expression. The divine is not one element among the elements of the world but the potentiality from which every element and every being arises.\n\nNa tad asti vinā mayā — nothing exists without me. This is an absolute statement about the relationship between the divine and existence. Existence is not the divine's product that then runs independently. It is continuously dependent on the divine, the way light depends on the sun — not created once and then left to illuminate on its own, but sustained moment to moment by the ongoing activity of the source.\n\nCarācaram — moving and non-moving. The granite mountain and the darting swallow. The ocean current and the still cave. The vast and the tiny, the silent and the loud, the ancient and the newborn. Not one of these exists apart from the divine. This is the comprehensive claim of the vibhūti teaching: look anywhere, and the divine is the ground of what you see.`
