      commentary: `Across the whole of Chapter 10, Krishna has been listing divine glories — I am this among the rivers, this among the mountains, this among the warriors, this among the seasons. The list is vast and meant to be overwhelming, to stretch the mind beyond its usual categories. And then this verse closes the chapter with a kind of divine understatement.\n\nAll of that, says Krishna — the sun, the moon, the ocean, the Himalaya, the sacred syllable, the logic in reasoning, the splendour in splendid things — all of that catalogue of infinity? That is just a fragment. Ekāṁśena — with one portion, one part. The entire manifest universe, with all its complexity and vastness and staggering variety, is sustained by one fragment of what the divine actually is.\n\nThe question this raises is not theological. It is existential. If this entire world is one fragment — what is the rest? What is the whole that this fragment is a fragment of? The Gita does not answer in words. It points. The answer is what you find when you stop at the edge of everything you can know and stay there long enough for something beyond knowing to become available.\n\nThis is how Chapter 10 ends: having stretched the mind as far as it will go, the teaching releases into silence. The universe is one piece. That is more than enough to sit with for a lifetime.`,
